Mrs. Edith W. Pierce, a nurse by training, became Philadelphia's first female city inspector of highways and street cleaning in 1913.  She founded a Junior Sanitation League to encourage young people to take an interest in healthy urban environments.  The Junior Sanitation League had over 10,000 members during her time, with each child wearing a pin that said &quot;For Clean Philadelphia Streets.&quot;  

<a href="http://chroniclingamerica.loc.gov/lccn/sn83045211/1914-09-19/ed-1/seq-10/;words=Philadelphia+Edith+Pierce+PIERCE+EDITH" rel="nofollow">chroniclingamerica.loc.gov/lccn/sn83045211/1914-09-19/ed-...</a>

She's mentioned in Martin V. Melosi, <i>Garbage in the Cities:  Refuse, Reform, and the Environment</i> (University of Pittsburgh Press 2004):  p. 106.

