A cropped version of this photo ran in The Sunday Oregonian. (Portland, Ore.) 1881-current, August 10, 1913, SECTION FIVE, Image 61 with the caption:
&quot;London society is keenly interested in the result of an interesting event in the Ducal family of the Roxburghes. Upon this event depends the important question of whether the titles and huge estates and properties of the Duke of Roxburghe shall be handed down in direct line or revert to the Duke's eldest brother, Lord Alastair Robert Innes-Ker. The Duke of Roxburghe married Miss May Goelet ten years ago and up to the present time there are no children. This marriage in May, 1903, was the biggest social society sensation of the season.&quot;
<a href="http://oregonnews.uoregon.edu/lccn/sn83045782/1913-08-10/ed-1/seq-61/" rel="nofollow">oregonnews.uoregon.edu/lccn/sn83045782/1913-08-10/ed-1/se...</a>

This photo ran in The Sunday Oregonian. (Portland, Ore.) 1881-current, August 10, 1913, SECTION FIVE, Image 61 with the caption:
&quot;Dr. Herbert E. Ives, of Philadelphia, says he has invented a substitute for daylight on which he has been at work for a dozen years. He says his new light has passed the test and is in every way equal to sunshine and the light of day. He has designed a powerful incandescent lamp with a special mantle, which is so placed in the top of a specially made cabinet that its rays are immediately beneath a reflector. This is made of metal and the light is forced downward through a series delicately colored screens. This light will be useful for dental work, sorting cigars, paper manufacture, diamond buyers, color printing, textile manufacture, dyeing and similar arts in which no light has been found which can satisfactorily take the place of daylight.&quot;
<a href="http://oregonnews.uoregon.edu/lccn/sn83045782/1913-08-10/ed-1/seq-61/" rel="nofollow">oregonnews.uoregon.edu/lccn/sn83045782/1913-08-10/ed-1/se...</a>

This photo ran in The Sunday Oregonian, August 10, 1913, SECTION FIVE, Image 61 with the caption:
&quot;Another society girl has gone on the stage. This time it is Angela Keir. She is a grandniece of the late General John A. Logan, who was long a Senator from Illinois. Miss Keir breaks into drama by way of vaudeville. She is now appearing In this city.&quot;
<a href="http://oregonnews.uoregon.edu/lccn/sn83045782/1913-08-10/ed-1/seq-61/" rel="nofollow">oregonnews.uoregon.edu/lccn/sn83045782/1913-08-10/ed-1/se...</a>

According to The Sunday Oregonian, August 24, 1913, SECTION FIVE, Image 57, this is not Dorothy, but her sister Gladys Deacon. The newspaper printed this photo with the caption:
&quot;Miss Gladys Deacon has been called the prettiest American girl in Europe. She has received more offers of marriage than any other American girl, but for some reason she is unmarried still. She has been courted by princes, counts, millionaires, and also by the Crown Prince of Germany. It is said that the Kaiser presented her with a valuable diamond and emerald necklace because she agreed not to encourage the Crown Prince. Her latest suitor was Lieutenant Oliphant, of the British Navy, and in fact her engagement to him was publicly announced, but the marriage has been put off frequently. &quot;Sickness&quot; was the last excuse. That was almost two years ago and the is still unmarried.&quot;
<a href="http://oregonnews.uoregon.edu/lccn/sn83045782/1913-08-24/ed-1/seq-57/" rel="nofollow">oregonnews.uoregon.edu/lccn/sn83045782/1913-08-24/ed-1/se...</a>

A cropped version of this photo ran in The Sunday Oregonian. (Portland, Ore.) 1881-current, August 10, 1913, SECTION FIVE, Image 61 with the caption:
&quot;William H. Murray, Known as '&quot;Alfalfa Bill,&quot; and &quot;the sage of Tishomingo,&quot; is the Congressman from Oklahoma who introduced in the House a resolution calling on President Wilson to use the land and naval forces of the United States to correct existing conditions in Mexico. Representative Murray was born near Collinsville, Grayson County, Tex. His mother died when he was 2 years old and he ran away from his father at 12 years of age. Hie has since &quot;punched&quot; cattle, chopped cordwood, worked in a brick yard, been a farm laborer, reported for and edited newspapers, taught school, practiced law and is now an extensive planter and farmer. He was educated in the common schools and in College Hill Institute. He served in the State House, of which he was Speaker for a time.&quot;
<a href="http://oregonnews.uoregon.edu/lccn/sn83045782/1913-08-10/ed-1/seq-61/" rel="nofollow">oregonnews.uoregon.edu/lccn/sn83045782/1913-08-10/ed-1/se...</a>

This photo ran in The Sunday Oregonian. (Portland, Ore.) 1881-current, August 03, 1913, SECTION FIVE, Image 61 with the caption
&quot;Colonel David Du Bose Gaillard, who has charge of the Pacific division of the Panama Canal, is a candidate to succeed Brigadier-General W. H. Bixby, Chief of Engineers, U.S.A., who will retire December 27. Other men mentioned for the position are Lieutenant Colonel W. L. Sibert, and Colonel G. W. Goethals. Colonel Gaillard was born in Fulton. S. C, in 1859, and is a graduate of the United States Military Academy.&quot;
