A cropped version of this photo ran in The Sunday Oregonian, July 13, 1913, SECTION FIVE, Image 59 with the caption:
&quot;The Grand Duke Michael is almost better known in England and Prance now than he is in his native Russia. He has been an exile from Russia be cause of his marriage. Like many of the Russian Grand Dukes, he found someone outside the court circle to love, and he married her. Such things are not unknown In other countries, but nowhere are they visited with such strict punishment as In Russia. The Grand Duke was practically banished. This was small punishment for him. The Russian Grand Dukes have always looked for their amusement in Paris rather than in St. Petersburg. The Grand Duke Michael, since his exile, has established a home in England and he spends much of his time In Paris and on the Riveria. His wife is ac counted one of the most beautiful women in continental society. She is known everywhere as  the Countess Torbay.&quot;
<a href="http://oregonnews.uoregon.edu/lccn/sn83045782/1913-07-13/ed-1/seq-59/" rel="nofollow">oregonnews.uoregon.edu/lccn/sn83045782/1913-07-13/ed-1/se...</a>

Prince (and Austrian army officer) Stanislaus Sulkowski married Marie Freese, a Los Angeles heiress, in August 1913.  But...while they were on honeymoon in Tahoe, a warrant was issued for his arrest under the Mann Act.  He was charged with bringing a Viennese laundress named Clara Melcher to the US for &quot;immoral purposes.&quot;  The honeymooning couple instead managed to escape to Vancouver and onto a ship bound for &quot;the Orient.&quot;  

