A cropped version of this photo ran in The Sunday Oregonian, July 13, 1913, SECTION FIVE, Image 59 with the caption:
&quot;Ostend, in Belgium, is one of the most fashionable bathing beaches of the Continental coast. Bathing machines are used by both men and women. They hire them for use as dressing-rooms. As they take off their street clothing and put on their bathing togs, the bath man hitches his horse to the machine and takes it out into water several feet deep. Then he unhitches his horse and returns for another machine. The theory is that by going into the water direct from the machine you preserve your modesty. When you are through your swim, you signal the bath man, and he comes and draws the machine back to shore. When there is a great rush of bathers, these bathing machines cannot find room in the shallow water, and they are drawn up in two or three rows, the last row being high and dry on the sand.&quot;
